  isbn = {978-94-007-0434-3},
  abstract = {The most economical and environmentally friendly strategy for limiting crop yield loss due to plant parasitic nematodes is the use of resistant plants. Several natural resistances have been introgressed into cultivars by breeding, few have been cloned and even less were successfully transferred to other species by genetic engineering. Furthermore, the choice of natural resistance genes is limited and often they confer resistance to only one species or even pathotype of nematodes. Based on growing molecular knowledge of plant parasitic nematodes and their infection cycle, gene technology offers a much wider toolbox to engineer nematode resistance into plants. This technology is not only useful for key nematode problems in developed countries (in crops such as potato and soybean) but certainly also in developing countries (in crops such as banana and rice). Recent developments indicate that countries in Asia and Africa are less hesitant to test and cultivate these crops than some European countries.},
