Abstract = {{Food production requires application of fertilizers containing
   phosphorus, nitrogen and potassium on agricultural fields in order to
   sustain crop yields. However modern agriculture is dependent on
   phosphorus derived from phosphate rock, which is a non-renewable
   resource and current global reserves may be depleted in 50-100 years.
   While phosphorus demand is projected to increase, the expected global
   peak in phosphorus production is predicted to occur around 2030. The
   exact timing of peak phosphorus production might be disputed, however it
   is widely acknowledged within the fertilizer industry that the quality
   of remaining phosphate rock is decreasing and production costs are
   increasing. Yet future access to phosphorus receives little or no
   international attention. This paper puts forward the case for including
   long-term phosphorus scarcity on the priority agenda for global food
   security. Opportunities for recovering phosphorus and reducing demand
   are also addressed together with institutional challenges. (C) 2009
